  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you stop a sunburn from peeling?",
  "response": "To help stop a sunburn from peeling and promote healing, follow these steps:\n\n1. **Cool the Skin**: Apply a cool, damp cloth to the affected area to soothe the skin and reduce inflammation. You can also take a cool bath or shower.\n\n2. **Moisturize**: Use a fragrance-free, gentle moisturizer to help keep the skin hydrated. Aloe vera gel is particularly effective as it has soothing properties.\n\n3. **Avoid Further Sun Exposure**: Stay out of the sun until the sunburn has healed. If you must go outside, wear protective clothing and use a broad-spectrum sunscreen with at least SPF 30.\n\n4. **Stay Hydrated**: Drink plenty of water to help your body heal from the inside out.\n\n5. **Avoid Picking at the Skin**: Peeling skin can be tempting to pick at, but doing so can lead to infection and scarring. Let the skin peel naturally.\n\n6. **Use Anti-Inflammatory Medications**: Over-the-counter options like ibuprofen or aspirin can help reduce inflammation and pain.\n\n7. **Apply Hydrocortisone Cream**: If the burn is particularly uncomfortable, a 1% hydrocortisone cream can help reduce itching and inflammation.\n\n8. **Avoid Harsh Products**: Steer clear of soaps, lotions, and creams that contain alcohol or other irritants.\n\nIf the sunburn is severe, covers a large area of your body, or is accompanied by symptoms like fever, chills, nausea, or severe pain, seek medical attention. A healthcare provider can offer additional treatments, such as prescription creams or oral steroids, to help manage your symptoms and prevent peeling.",
